SIMPLE: squawk
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Squawk
<hw>Squawk</hw> <pr>(skw⟦add⟧k)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Squawked</conjf>
<pr>(skw⟦add⟧kt)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Squawking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[See <er>Squeak</er>.]</ety>
<def>To utter a shrill, abrupt scream; to squeak harshly.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Squawking thrush</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the
missel turush; -- so called from its note when alarmed.</cd>
<mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Squawk</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Squawk
<hw>Squawk</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Act of squawking; a
harsh squeak.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The American night heron. See
under <er>Night</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Squawk duck</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the
bimaculate duck (<spn>Anas glocitans</spn>). It has patches of reddish
brown behind, and in front of, each eye.</cd> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Squawl</ent>⟦br⟧
